values:
I like how one of my New Year's resolutions was to write on this more...I believe this is my third entry of 2010? Oh well.

I had my first real audition last month. It was for the second clarinet/bass clarinet spot for Opera Cleveland...a company that puts on 4 operas a season with about 4 performances each opera. It wasn't well paid...I believe it was about $25/hour for rehearsals and $80/show, but it would've been a nice resume builder. Anywho, Inhyung was supposed to take the audition with me, but as the last weekend approached she backed out because of the problems she was still having with the bass clarinet. I was kind of bummed to have to drive 8 hours to Cleveland alone, but hey, I like to drive and this is what I'm supposed to be doing, right? Taking auditions...balls to the walls.

I stayed at a friend of a friend's house in Cleveland for the night, and then woke up the next morning at 6:30am to get ready for the 8:15am drawing of slots to determine order of audition. 21 people were registered to be there, but only 15 showed up. A pretty small number, but for a pretty insignificant job. I drew 9th and warmed up in the group warm-up space, and about 20 minutes later I was escorted to my own warm up area. After another 30 or so minutes I was taken to the audition room, where I was told to play the first page of Mozart, the tiny Traviata excerpt, and the hard-ass Rosenkavalier excerpt. Mozart was fine, except for the last 3 notes not coming out in the run because I didn't cover my right hand all the way. Gah. Traviata was mediocre because a giant truck was backing up outside of the building and I couldn't hear myself. Ugh. And of course, Rosenkavalier was awesome. I nailed its ass. But by then it was probably too late to matter. So it goes.

I sat around for about 20 minutes and then we were all called upstairs for the results. 1 person from our group of 8 advanced...not me....which would go with the 2 who advanced from the previous group to the next round.

I shrugged my shoulders and walked back to my car with the 11 other clarinetists, and decided to just go back to New Haven and go to work the next day. I fueled up, and was back in New Haven 8 hours later.

All in all it was a great learning experience, and I'm looking forward to getting better and better at the process. My next audition is for the President's Own Marine Band on August 30-31. I'm hoping to get past the first round, but won't be too upset if I don't. All I can do is my best. 

Cheers.

So I just got back from Boston where I auditioned for the Pacific Music Festival. Jenn and Inhyung came along and auditioned too, so we made a nice day of it. It's great to be only a little over 2 hours away from Boston, 1.5 hours from New York, and 4 hours from Vermont. SO great.

The audition itself went okay. I was ironically most unhappy with how my Mozart went, seeing how it is the technically least-demanding of all I had to play. The (easy) runs weren't very clean. Very weird. I think it had to do with nerves, and mostly getting used to sitting down and playing for strangers. After the Mozart things got easier. I was asked to play Shostakovich 9 next (the fast movement), and aside from playing the beginning 'piano' parts louder than I wanted, it went pretty well. The runs were clean (even that really pesky one!) and I made it all the way through in the one breath. Holler. They asked for Beethoven 8 next, and I remember kind of rushing throughout it. And the first high 'g' bit being a little too soft. As in I hope it wasn't just me who heard those 4 notes or so. Oh well. Then the bass excerpts were heard. Well, just the Stravinsky excerpts. And those went SWIMMINGLY. Couldn't believe it. Even the pesky 'piano' part that doesn't like to sound even. 

The festival takes only 4 or so clarinets out of probably 1,000 who audition for it worldwide. It takes place in Japan and is about 4 weeks long over the summer. I won't get my hopes too high, because c'mon...4 clarinets?! But it was free to apply for, free travel and tuition/room/board if I get in, and fairly cheap to travel to audition for as it was split three ways. Traveling with my friends was a blast, as well as eating Mexican food, drinking a Sam Adams Winter Ale, and stocking up on some DELISH stuff from Trader Joe's on the way out of town (pumpkin seeds, little whole grain chocolate chip cookies, a $6 six-pack of wheat beer, $3 White Zin, Jarlsberg cheese, and whole-grain crackers). Mmmmm.

The frosty on the way home didn't hurt, either :0)

Welp, they're all in. I got into all of the schools I auditioned for, and am pretty happy about the whole experience. If anything, it makes me feel more confident in my playing. Here are the stats (they're all per year):

Northwestern: Offered me full tuition ($38,000)
Eastman: Offered me about half tuition ($9,800)
CCM: Offered me 90% tuition ($18,700)
Rice: Offered me 75% tuition ($21,000)
Yale: Full tuition for all students ($27,000), waiting to hear if I will be getting a stipend

Right now I'm leaning towards Yale. There are only 6 clarinets in the studio, so I will automatically be getting many opportunities to play. The Yale School of Music is comprised of only graduate students, so I will only be interacting with intelligent, serious musicians. The clarinet professor is David Shifrin, probably the most prolific clarinetist of my time. Not only do I study his recordings of chamber and solo pieces (which I love to death), he is an internationally-renowned endorser of classical music, and holds the position of Artistic Director of the Lincoln Center. He seemed very nice and down-to-earth at my audition, was very friendly, and gave me good vibes. Not a creepo like some of these guys.

Walking around Yale was a really neat experience. Coming from a large university with budget cuts every year, it was nice being in an atmosphere where the arts and education were emphasized and wholly supported. The campus was absolutely beautiful, and the town was inviting and alive. It also wouldn't hurt to be living right between New York and Boston.

So, I think that's what's going to happen. I'm excited!

I am so ready to start the next chapter in my life. I'm ready to move away, and to begin again. I just got back from rehearsal with TSO, and thankfully it reminded me that no matter what crap is going on in my life, music makes me happy again. I mean, it's a pretty boring program (Tchaik Romeo and Juliet Overture and Schumann 2 <yawn>), but I'm still enthralled and revitalized. This is what I am meant to do. Sit and play. All of the other crap washes away. I am ready to move away, sit and play, learn, and be rid of the crap. Less than 3 months now. Please come swiftly so I can be happy again.

Sorry about that last crap. Nobody needs that. I just need to stop wallowing.

Anyway, things have turned out differently this semester then planned, but still good. Because I'm playing in TSO Feb. 14th, I can't play in the first UPO concert, which is also the 14th. Bummer because I was assigned principal in 2/3 pieces (one of which is Sibelius 2), but okay because I'm going to be playing 2nd to Dr. Bish in Tchaikovsky's Romeo and Juliet Fantasy-Overture and Schumann 2, and get to hear Dr. Kowalsky play the 'X' Concerto. So pros and cons, I suppose.

Class-wise, I'm taking Woodwind Lit, 20th Century Styles (a theory class which I will pass with the help of Stephanie), and Tennis..along with the usual lessons and excerpts class. Tennis will be good. I played today and really enjoyed myself with Nick. I want to actually try to learn the rules and how to actually do a backswing. Those are my goals. Hah.

More some other time.

Oh yea. It's the fall of my senior year. I can't believe how fast it's going by. This time next year I'm going to be somewhere else in the country. (Yea, I'm not brave enough to look into studying in Europe or anything...or even the west coast for that matter.) Okay, so more on those possible other places. Here's my list of possible grad schools:

Rice- In Houston, TX. Pros- Super small studios (only 8 clarinets!!!), AMAZING orchestral program, NO BAND. Cons- It's in the south. I hate the south.
Yale- Pros- FREE if accepted. Small school, only grad students. Cons- Not a lot of playing experience in school ensembles/orchestras.
University of Michigan- Pros- Awesome teacher, really good program all around. Cons- Another big university like FSU.
Cincinnati College-Conservatory of Music- Pros- Awesome teacher, small school. Cons- price?
Northwestern- Pros- In Chicago, could also study with bass clarinetist, family in Chicago area. Cons- not the premiere clarinet place anymore.
Eastman- In Rochester, NY. Pros- Everything about the music program is amazing. Cons- Location, cost.

So there you have it. I've been in contact with the professor from CCM. I'm going to take a lesson with him in December. He's also one of the clarinet guys at Music Academy of the West, a kickass summer program. So maybe if I make a good impression I might get an "in" at Music Academy as well?

I've also been in touch with Michael Webster in Rice. Sounds like a really good guy. Plus, Dr. K and Dr. Bish are friends with him. So maybe I'll get one of the 4 open spots they have for next fall? We'll see.

In other news, I'm taking two academic classes, 3 ensembles (UPO, Wind Orchestra, Mas N Steel), my lesson, and excerpts class. I'm playing in a quintet with some awesome peeps, and we're performing Barber's "Summer Music" twice in November. In the spring we're going to be playing the Poulenc Sextet....so I'm getting in some good quintet rep this year.

Oh, and I made TSO! I'm playing bass in a couple of concerts this year, and getting paid to sit next to my two clarinet professors and play bass clarinet. How awesome is that?!?!

Anyway, time for UPO!

Wow, it's been a while. Anyway, Brevard was wonderful. Playing in orchestra everyday, playing in a good chamber group, and just mingling with really talented musicians was a wonderful thing for me to be doing this summer. Plus, anything beats being in Port Charlotte. The clarinet professor there was Steve Cohen, the prof at Northwestern. He really seemed to like me, and could probably give me a lot of money to go to Northwestern for my masters. But he was a little...awkward. He was a good teacher, but hard to read. But Chicago would be a pretty cool place to live. And I would get to study with him and the bass clarinetist of the Chicago Symphony...Lawrie Bloom. I'm definitely applying, but we'll see what happens. 

So, I made principal in UPO again. The first concert is next Friday/Saturday and my rotation is only playing in the overture (Overture to Nabucco). Bummer. But hopefully I'll be in the rotation for the big piece next concert, which is Mendelssohn 5. That's a pretty sweet symphony.

More later. Gotta go.

So I'm here at my second day in Brevard, North Carolina at a Music Festival. I'll be here until August 11th, for those of you who care. It's so gorgeous here. I'm literally in the forest of a mountain. The place is 140 sq. acres on the side of a mountain, complete with streams, rocky (and slippery) paths, bugs, and 60-yr old cabins. But it's nice. I'll go more into detail later. This is my first time on a computer in a few days, so I've got some surfing to do right now. There are only 3 little spots on the campus that get wireless, so compy time is precious.

Anyway, it's .. "Quiz time, bitches."

Please copy mine below, erase my answers putting yours in their place then post it in your journal! Please elaborate on the questions that would benefit from elaboration! One-Word-Answers seldom help anyone out :)

1. First Name: Sara

2. Age: 21

3. Location: Right now: Brevard, NC. Usually: Tallahassee, FL. Hometown: Port Charlotte, FL

4. Occupation: Going into my senior year at FSU in Clarinet Performance

5. Partner?: Does that mean boyfriend? If so, Dannel!

6. Kids: None...yuck.

7. Brothers/Sisters: Sister Kari, 19. Half sister Julie, 28

8. Pets: Abby, the most awesome cat ever. Miss you Abbers!

9. List the 3-5 biggest things going on in your life:

1. Playing with professional musicians from all over the United States this summer
2. Thinking about choosing grad schools to audition for in the Spring
3. Wondering if I'll be able to survive in this business

10) Where and for what did you go to school for?:

Currently at FSU studying Clarinet Performance. Gonna graduate next Spring and then who knows!

11) Parents?

Mom: Unemployed/disabled. She was an RN for like 20 years and then was diagnosed about 3 years back with Multiple Sclerosis and was told that should couldn't work anymore. It sucks mostly because she's only like 54.

Dad: Flooring Specialist at GCO, but is looking for a new job (his boss SUCKS)

12) Who are some of your closest friends?: Nick, Casey, Sonia, Shino, Kyle!

It's been a while, and all I really have to say is that I dropped my phone in the toilet this morning at work.

lol


I'm still here in Tallahassee...working, practicing, running, playing guitar hero, and baking. That's about it. I leave either Thursday or Friday to spend a couple days with my sister in Gainesville, and then I head on down to PC for a couple of weeks. After that...Brevard! I'm starting to get really excited.

Dannel has been in Europe all month. It's pretty difficult having a new relationship with somebody when they're always gone, but we'll see how it unfolds. Hopefully he bought me some awesome European chocolate...mmm.

I'll start posting more. Promise.

I got into Brevard!!!!! I was selected as one of the four clarinets in the upper division! I will be rotating in on the faculty orchestra and playing in the college orchestra! I'm so freaking excited! 8 weeks in North Carolina playing in an orchestra....amazing. Nick got a stage management internship there too! So we're going to be there together!!!!!!

In other news, I love playing in orchestra. Even though I was shafted and am not playing in the big piece (Capriccio Espagnol) next concert, playing the Beethoven Overture to Lenore is still really neat. Just making this amazing music with other musicians is enough to make me happy for the rest of the day.

Anyway, I'm off. Peace.

Man, I need to listen to my classical playlist on random more...there's some good shit on there that I never listen to!

So...I've started seeing someone. He's from this group of graduate friends I've been hanging out with since last semester. He's cute, smart, funny, talented...fits all of the pre-requisites. I'm just a little scared because, well, relationships are scary. I mean, he kind of likes to just say how he's feeling...things like, "you're so amazing" and "I'm so happy I met you" and all of these other things that sort of put a lot of pressure on me. We're completely comfortable around each other and all, and I just want it to be something fun and enjoyable without a lot of stress. I've got too much of that in my life as it is.  We're both really busy with school, so at least I don't feel bad about not being able to spend every minute with him...because he can't either. Soooooo I'll just see what happens, right?

I'm really anxious to find out about my summer auditions! The applications were due March 1st, so I'm guessing it'll be a few more weeks before I hear anything. Nick got hired as a stage manager at Brevard this summer. It'll be soooooo cool if we're both there. ::crosses fingers::

Off to the beach tomorrow with Sonia! I miss seeing her! I need more girly-girl time in my life. I should call Tiffany more. She's one of them girly-girls.
'

...and nothing special has happened.

This semester has been all about preparing for my audition CDs for summer music festivals. I really want to get into Brevard. It's 7 weeks of orchestral training in North Carolina. It would just be freaking amazing to play in an orchestra all summer, you know? I should have good odds of getting in...the clarinet instructor, Steve Cohen, gave me two lessons last summer in Indiana...and liked me. Told me to apply again, ::wink wink:: So hopefully I'll get in. My other option is the Chautaqua Music Festival in upstate NY. Basically the same deal, only they take 3 clarinets where Brevard takes 5. So not much of a backup option...but whatever. I'm also going to try to get into a week-long festival outside of Quebec City called "Domaine Forget". Larry Combs from the CSO and a couple clarinetists from the Montreal Symphony will be teaching lessons and masterclasses. I should have good odds getting into there...only the plane ticket will cost more than the actual festival. Oh well. So basically, the idea this summer is not to be home. I like that.

So I've been getting some nice compliments lately on the weight I've lost. I guess it's easier to notice after the winter layers of clothes come off. I'm down 22 lbs from August. Not numerically much, but my body is definitely a-changin'. A couple weeks ago I started running 3 times a week. I NEVER thought I would enjoy running, but it's really stress-relieving. I run at 7 on Tuesdays and Thursdays at the gym for about 2 miles before class, and then once on the weekends. It feels good.

So there's this guy. He's nice, funny, musically talented, and 'my type'. He's obviously interested in me. However, I have been informed of some bad things in this guy's past that seem NOTHING like him. But my informant is very reliable. This guy has been nothing but perfect, yet I can't help thinking of how he may actually be. Ugh. Why can't nice guys actually be nice? This is the second time this sort of thing has happened to me. Oh well. Maybe I'll just keep hanging out with him and his crowd and see what happens? I don't know.

Orchestra concert tomorrow night. One of the pieces I'm in is the Rachmaninoff Piano Concerto no. 1. It's really pretty. Y'all should listen to it sometime.

Oot.

Thank goodness it was just my craziness. Apparently I didn't play that God-awful. Good.

I made co-principal in UPO (the undergrad orchestra). That's cool. I'm playing in 2/3 pieces in the February concert, but I don't know what I'll be playing in the April concert (when we're playing Capriccio Espagnol...a big clarinet piece). The other principal, Melanie, might get the Capriccio solo...but oh well. She's a senior. We'll see what happens.

So I also auditioned on bass clarinet for the Rite of Spring that the USO (graduate orchestra) is doing in February. I talked to Dr. Bish this morning, and she said that while I didn't get the Rite of Spring spot, they were very impressed with my bass skills and decided to put me on bass in Wind Orchestra (grad band). It's a solo part, so it's a big responsibility. She said that it would be good to work on my bass skills more this semester because it's something I'm good at, and something that could potentially get me a job and gigs in the future. She said that she actually has made more money playing bass than clarinet...so it's a good skill to have. Money is good. I'll definitely consider auditioning on bass in the future.

So....yay for no Symphonic Band! I get to keep my Spanish Lit. class after all! Holla!

God I hope that my audition wasn't as bad as I think it was. I know I'm my worst critic and all, but man my trills sucked in Capriccio. And apparently I was rushing because Dr. K started beating his arm in tempo...

FUCK

I just don't want to be in Symphonic Band...

let the powers that be put me back in Wind Orchestra....PLEASE.

UGHGHGHGHGHG



In other news, my bass clarinet audition wasn't half bad. The first part Dr. K had me do again without rushing (imagine that), the second part I was told to do again with more air, and the third part was apparently good because I saw Dr. K do a big surprised look over at Dr. B. We'll see.

Now I have to freaking wait until Thursday afternoon. AND I have to have somebody read the results to me over the phone because I'll be in Tampa.

UGHGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGG  Please let this be an over-reaction.

So I was up until 3:30 writing a paper for music history. No big deal. I'm always procrastinating on papers...even the big ones. Anyway, I get up at 7 as usual, feeling oddly awake. Maybe it was the Christmas music on the radio. Yea. Maybe that was it. It appears as if my alarm clock station has switched over to Christmas tunes...but I like it. Except for the whole laying in bed for 4 songs and humming along before actually getting up. Anyway, I get to school and park and take my everyday brief walk to the school of music. I'm walking up the hill and trip on the sidewalk, as usual. You see, these sidewalks are treacherous. They're uneven, old, bumpy, and just begging for danger. So I'm in the process of tripping (this is occurring in slow motion, naturally) and realize that this is no ordinary trip. Nope. I am moving too fast to get out of this one without going completely down. And so I do. So there I am...diving face-first into the pavement. Many things are flashing in front of me...mainly my banana and cell phone that I had been holding. I end up landing on my, get this- left elbow, right hand, and left knee. Don't know why. Don't know how. I quickly jump back up, grab my banana off the ground like nothing happened, and proceed up the hill. But then I hear "maim?!" I turn and see a girl holding my phone and a guy next to her trying not to laugh. I get my phone from her and the guy says "bad morning?" I reply, "yep, bad morning...shit." 

After spanish I realized that my baton snapped in my backpack. I don't know if it was because of the fall, but a broken $30 baton is still no good.

My knee is horribly sore and my elbow was scraped through my sweater...and it hurts in that sucky rug-burn kind of way.

Let's hope the rest of today goes a little more smoothly.

I just got home from a bar! I didn't get carded! I think it was my new leather jacket! Whoo! My first bar! It was fun! And I bumped into some guy and he said "excuse me" and brushed his hand against my boob! My first feel-up! "I'm totally putting this on livejournal" , I thought.

Hah!



I love bacardi and diets!

I did something out of my schedule on Wednesday. I was spontaneous. After Wind Orchestra, Janet and Morgan asked me if I wanted to go to dinner with them and Shino....I said, "ummmm" and finally said yes. And it was nice. This got me to thinking...what would I do if I started seeing someone? Could I fit them into my schedule? Would I have it in my power to be spontaneous and hang out with whenever they wanted, or would this relationship be "by appointment only"? Nobody special is in mind. However, I have been talking more and more online with this kid in one of my classes. But I don't think there's anything.

Am I too focused on school and practicing and my future to have a social life? I mean, I rarely do things with people anymore...but I don't feel the need to. I am happy being alone a lot of the time because I am in control of my schedule. Maybe it's the 3-5 hours alone in a practice room everyday...or my best friends being theatre majors who are never home at night. I don't know. I mean, Casey went to Wal-Mart with Patrick at midnight last night. They just got up and went. Everything about that is crazy to me. Am I an old lady?

In other news, the weather has been beautiful. The 60s are lovely. It makes me want to just be north..say, in Rochester. Unless I go somewhere else to take a lesson and just feel an instant connection with the professor, I'm going to make Rochester my first choice. I can't wait. I want to be one of those cool grads, sleeping in and then practicing all day and going to rehearsals....and giving a lesson or two.

I wanted to be Wilma from the Flintstones for Halloween, but I just realized that the first of many Halloween parties is tonight, and I am going to be tied up until 10:30, with only a small break from 6-7:30. I'm playing in the pit for Into the Woods tonight, subbing for someone. When will I have time to make my costume? Oye. Maybe I'll just be Lucy again...I still have my old dress.

I wonder wonder wonder....what it's like to be, say, a psychology major. Or an english major. I can't even imagine what it's like to have 2 classes a day...2 hours of responsibility. I mean, of course they have homework, and probably a job...but the typical college kid has 2 hours of class a day, 8 hours of work (at most), and 3 hours of homework, right? I'm on my second day of being at school from 8am-10:30pm. Sure, I'm getting paid to sub for Morgan in Into the Woods, but even without that I'm here until at least 6. I'm not complaining....just wondering what the typical kid does. I HATE walking by kids and overhearing them say how they're so stressed because they have 3 classes today. Wow. 3 hours at school. How terrible. This is the time of your life...time to learn...time to grow. You'll never get that back. Never.

I love my major. Sitting and playing in orchestra has once again re-affirmed that this is what I want to do for the rest of my life. Period. End of discussion. It's a very nice feeling. It'll be a better feeling when I graduate from here, get my masters, and actually find a job... but I'm happy for now.

I wish I could find more gigs. I love the concept of going to school and practicing all day, having a dinner break, and gigging somewhere until 10 or whatever. It'd be the perfect job. I just feel so crappy working 1 or 2 days a week at Michaels. I want to pull in more money. A plus about subbing for Morgan in Into the Woods is that I've become pretty sociable with Tom (the musical director), and I think he likes me. Hopefully that'll keep my name in his head for future work.

Tomorrow I'm only here from 8am-8:30pm. That'll be a nice change.   :0P

I got my Selmer B-flat clarinets today! I tried the 3 out in my lesson with Dr. Bish, and I picked the one I want! It's beautiful! It has such a gorgeous and full sound. My 40 year-old Buffet clarinet just wasn't cutting it anymore. Now I have a matching set of new Selmers! Hooray!

"Hairspray" was such great movie. I saw it like 3 times...a while back. I don't know why I'm bringing it up now. Maybe it was a line in "Mr. Holland's Opus" that I'm watching now..."Congratulations Mr. Russ, you just found the beat." I love "Mr. Holland's Opus". Such a great movie.





Moving on. I am REALLY excited about this semester. Over the summer I reached another plateau in my music. I'm excited about planning my week of practicing. I'm excited about lessons, learning new excerpts, and my junior recital in the spring. I made the University Philharmonia Orchestra...the undergrad orchestra here. I am one of 4 rotating clarinets, the other 3 are seniors. I'm playing principle on two of the four pieces on the first concert. They're not very difficult (Haydn and Schubert), but hey, at least I'm playing in orchestra. No other juniors can say that. I was also assigned to the E-flat clarinet in Symphonic Band (I was very excited!), but right after our first rehearsal Dr. Bish found me and asked me if I wanted to play in the Wind Orchestra...the top band here. It's mostly grad students with a few undergrads here and there. I OF COURSE said yes! I'm going to be playing 3rd, but I'm one of 7 clarinets...not 20 like in Symphonic Band. Wind Orchestra is basically a professional wind group. We had our first rehearsal today...it's just a completely different atmosphere. It's like we're adults at work instead of kids playing in a band. I'm really happy that I don't have to put up with Dunnigan (director of the Symphonic Band) anymore.

What the hell do I have to do?

Today is my last day of Phase 1 of the South Beach Diet. For those of you who don't know, The South Beach Diet is broken into three phases. Phase 1 is two weeks. In those two weeks you cannot eat carbs or fruit. The purpose is to clean up your insulin and blood sugar levels/tolerance. It's supposed to clear the slate. I'm pretty proud of myself, I must say. Anyone who knows me knows that I love bread and snacks and carbs of all kinds....and that I LOVE fruit. But for two weeks now I haven't had a single piece of bread or any carbs of any kind. I only cheated once...a tiny bit. Last Saturday I got a chicken salad from Chili's. The chicken was breaded...and instead of scraping the skin off I ate it as it was. Oh, and I had it with a rum and coke. (You're not supposed to have alcohol of any kind.) So it wasn't like I scarfed down a piece of cake. I don't have a scale, but I'm going home tomorrow and there'll be a scale there. Most people lose 8-12lbs after Phase 1....so I'm anxious to see where I'm at. I'll update tomorrow.

Phase 2 starts tomorrow. This is where I can introduce good carbs and fruit back into my diet...gradually. More than anything I went on South Beach to learn about what I should be eating. Both sides of my family have struggled with heart and weight problems...and I don't want to have to worry about that. I've learned a lot by reading the South Beach book. So, beginning tomorrow I can have a serving of good carbs once a day and a piece of fruit twice a day. (Good carbs meaning brown rice, whole grain bread, wheat english muffins, etc.) I can add more after a little while, but Phase 2 is about seeing what I can eat to keep losing weight...so I don't want to push it.

Phase 3 (after two weeks of phase 2) is the rest of my life. It's all about remembering the good carbs and all of the rules. It's about eating right and living healthy. If I fall off the wagon and gain weight back, I can just go and do Phase 1 again. I'm pretty happy with it.

Overall, I've been alright with the diet. Instead of Ice Cream at night I've had sugar-free ice pops...and they're great. I really miss cereal, though. Starting tomorrow I can have it again, but just the high-fiber good kind. It'll probably take a while to find one that doesn't taste like cardboard, though. And then I'll have to decide if I want cereal in the morning or bread with my dinner. That'll be a little difficult.

I'm ready for a new and healthier me!

So I've definitely decided that after grad school the best possible job for me would be in a military band out of Washington. Yea, I get sick of playing in band. Yea, I'm pretty liberal and don't really care about the military. But $46,000 starting pay and full military benefits is pretty awesome. And it's not limited to band. There are chamber groups for special occasions or dinners at the White House. There are a bunch of travel and solo opportunities. This is something I'm really going to shoot for.

However, in order to be in a military band, like the Marine Band, you have to also meet all of the health and background requirements that the Marines do. Like height and weight, for instance. After checking their website, I, as a woman of 63 inches, am 5 lbs overweight. Overweight. As in, I couldn't be in the Marine Band right now because I'd be considered too heavy. That's pretty depressing...especially for a person who's been self conscious her entire life of her weight. Bummer.

July 1-15 I'll be at Ball State University in Muncie, IN at a chamber music festival. After that I go to Tallahassee to work a few weeks, then back here for 2 weeks to work the marching band camp. Then to start my junior year. Holla. I'm really excited about taking only music classes and my spanish minor...no more bullshit liberal arts requirements. Oh, and I'm really excited about orchestra.
